# AGENTS.md

> Written by `metaldoc init`. This is the canonical agent guidance file; if your
> tool reads `CLAUDE.md`, symlink or copy it from here.

## Metal Development

Use `metaldoc` to discover exact, current Metal APIs **before** writing code. Do
not guess signatures, selectors, or MSL builtins — they vary by SDK version and
Metal toolchain, and `metaldoc` reflects the ones actually installed here.

```bash
metaldoc lookup MTL::Device::newBuffer        # C++ name
metaldoc lookup newBufferWithLength:options:  # by ObjC selector
metaldoc msl thread_position_in_grid          # MSL builtin
metaldoc search texture --format json         # discovery
```

Prefer `--format json` when you need structured fields. Every result carries:

- `signature` — exact C++ declaration
- `overloads` — all overloads of the symbol
- `selector` — the Objective-C selector (cross-language join key)
- `ownership` — `owned` (+1, you must release) or `borrowed` (do not release)
- `source` — `path:line` in the project's actual metal-cpp headers
- `availability` / `doc` — when ObjC enrichment is indexed

If a query is ambiguous, `metaldoc` returns candidate symbol IDs and a non-zero
exit code. Re-run with a candidate ID or an owner-qualified name; do not pick one
at random.

## metal-cpp Memory Ownership (READ FIRST)

This is the most common source of Metal bugs. metal-cpp follows Cocoa's
Create/Get naming rules. When in doubt, check the `ownership` field from
`metaldoc lookup`.

- Methods named `new*`, `alloc*`, `copy*`, `mutableCopy*`, or `*Create*` return
  an **owned (+1)** object. You must release it, or wrap it in a smart pointer.
- **All other** methods return a **borrowed (autoreleased)** object. Do **not**
  release it. Call `->retain()` only if you must keep it past the current scope.

Prefer `NS::SharedPtr` over manual `retain`/`release`:

```cpp
#include <Metal/Metal.hpp>

// +1 owned  -> TransferPtr takes ownership of the existing +1 reference
NS::SharedPtr<MTL::Buffer> buffer =
    NS::TransferPtr(device->newBuffer(length, MTL::ResourceStorageModeShared));

// +0 borrowed -> RetainPtr adds a reference you are responsible for
NS::SharedPtr<MTL::Device> dev = NS::RetainPtr(MTL::CreateSystemDefaultDevice());
```

Scope per-frame transient objects in an autorelease pool:

```cpp
NS::SharedPtr<NS::AutoreleasePool> pool = NS::TransferPtr(NS::AutoreleasePool::alloc()->init());
// ... create command buffers, encoders, drawables ...
// pool drains when it goes out of scope
```

Manual form (only when you cannot use `NS::SharedPtr`):

```cpp
MTL::CommandQueue* queue = device->newCommandQueue(); // +1 owned
// ... use queue ...
queue->release();                                     // required
```

## Errors

Metal reports errors through `NS::Error**` out-parameters. A null return value
means failure; inspect the error before continuing.

```cpp
NS::Error* error = nullptr;
NS::SharedPtr<MTL::Library> library = NS::TransferPtr(
    device->newLibrary(source, /*options=*/nullptr, &error));

if (!library) {
    const char* msg = error ? error->localizedDescription()->utf8String()
                            : "unknown error";
    // handle compilation/runtime failure using `msg`
}
```

## MSL (shaders)

MSL is the GPU-side language, not the host API. Look up address spaces, entry
qualifiers, resource bindings, and built-in attributes:

```bash
metaldoc msl device                      # address space
metaldoc msl kernel                      # entry qualifier
metaldoc msl '[[buffer(n)]]'             # resource binding
metaldoc msl '[[thread_position_in_grid]]'
metaldoc msl metal::dot                  # stdlib function
```

Do not assume an MSL function exists or has a given overload — confirm with
`metaldoc msl` first, since the MSL standard library tracks the installed Metal
toolchain version.

## Workflow

1. Before calling any Metal API, run `metaldoc lookup` (host) or `metaldoc msl`
   (shader) to confirm the exact name, signature, and ownership.
2. Wrap owned objects in `NS::SharedPtr` at the point of creation.
3. Check `NS::Error**` out-parameters and null returns.
4. Re-run `metaldoc` rather than relying on memory of older Metal versions.
